$ Oracle Initialization Parameters
@ init parameters

Init parameters are (named) *configuration parameters* whose values control the operation of an ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/architecture/instance.

{ Storing values

  The values of the init parameters are stored in
    ‚ÄĘ so called *PFILE* (= parameter file which is as manually editable textual file and cannot contain PDB-specific values) or
    ‚ÄĘ *SPFILE* (‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/architecture/database/files/server-parameter-file[server parameter file] which is a binary file and is modified by the instance).

  One of these files is read when an instance is started up. The only required parameter is `‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/adminstration/init-parameters/db/name`, all other parameters have default values.

  After the instance has read the values, they are maintained in memory where the non-static parameters can be also changed.

}
{ Types

  There are the following types:
    ‚ÄĘ Dervied parameters: The actual values are calculated from the values of other parameters (but can still be altered by the DBA)
    ‚ÄĘ Operating System dependent values
    ‚ÄĘ Variable parameters (Can be set for the current session with `alter session set <parameter>=<new_value>`)
    ‚ÄĘ Dynamic parameters (Can be set for the entire database only. Modifying them in memory takes immediate effect after executing `alter system set <parameter>=<new_value>`)
    ‚ÄĘ Static parameters (they cannot be changed in memory, thus the instance needs to be restarted to modify them after executing `alter system set <parameter>=<new_value> scope=spfile`)

  Starting with ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/Releases-and-versions/21c, it's possible to use ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/adminstration/init-parameters/_expressions[expressions] to specify values for init parameters.

}
{ Querying the values of init parameters

  The actual values of the initialization parameters can be queried from ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/installed/dynamic-performance-views/parameter/index[`v$parameter`]:
code {
select
   value
from
   v$parameter
where
   name = '‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/adminstration/init-parameters/memory/target[memory_target]';
code }

  In ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/SQL-Plus and ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/SQLcl, a value can also be shown with `show parameter`.
code {
rene@ORA19> show parameter ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/adminstration/init-parameters/memory/target;
code }

  In order to query modified values in other ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/architecture/session[sessions],
 `‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/tools/oradebug/dump/modified_parameters` can be used.

}
{ Hidden (underscore) parameters

  Parameters starting with an underscore are so-called ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/adminstration/init-parameters/_hidden[hidden parameters]. These are not documented.

}
{ Modifying parameter values

  Parameter values can be changed with ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/SQL/statement/nouns/system/alter[`alter system`] or
  ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/SQL/statement/nouns/session/set/init-param[`alter session set init-parameter = ‚Ä¶`].

  Changing a parameter value in the ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/architecture/database/files/server-parameter-file.
code {
‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/SQL/statement/nouns/system/alter[alter system] set ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/adminstration/init-parameters/memory/target[memory_target]='300M' scope=spfile;
code }

  See also ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/architecture/database/files/server-parameter-file#ora-spfile-alter-system-scope[the `scope` clause in `alter system set ‚Ä¶`] statement.

  On a session level, parameters can be changed with ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/SQL/statement/nouns/session#ora-alter-session-set[`alter session set init_parameter = value`].

  The value of a limited set of initialization parameters can be set for the duration of the ‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/SQL/statement/execution[execution of an SQL statement] with the
 `‚Üí development/databases/Oracle/SQL/hints/list/opt/param` hint.

}
